<HEADLINE>
<P>
DISCOVERY OF EXPLOSIVES FORCES MAJOR EVACUATION IN MONTEREY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Hundreds of homes were evacuated for more than seven hours Thursday after 
several cases of old explosives were found in a vacant house, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
 There were no reported injuries, said city spokesman Fred Cohn. 
</P>
<P>
 Authorities removed more than 300 pounds of the explosive, believed to be 
dynamite, from the home. The explosives were detonated at a city beach about 8 
p.m. 
</P>
<P>
 The north Monterey home where the explosives were found had been vacant for 
some time and was recently sold, Cohn said. 
</P>
<P>
 The explosives were found about 10 a.m. by house cleaners, he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Authorities evacuated several hundred nearby houses and apartments. 
</P>
<P>
 California 1 was closed until about 7 p.m. 
</P>
</TEXT>
