<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Jerry Hicks 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 HERE'S THE KEY: Shirley Piha, 65, of Newport Beach went to Santa Ana Chrysler 
Plymouth to have her car appraised. Before she left, she says, she was 
pressured into buying a car she didn't want by salesmen who kept stalling when 
she asked for her keys back. Piha settled her lawsuit this week for $35,000. . 
. . Dealership owner Mike Shepard, who denies her version, is steaming: "You 
can't afford to take a chance in court in this country any more." But Piha's 
lawyer, Aurora Harris counters: "It's an old sales tactic that's being used 
more often." 
</P>
<P>
 NO TORTOISE: Were you around the Huntington Beach Pier when those 14 people 
took off on the Trans America Footrace June 18? Five of them crossed the finish 
line at New York's Central Park -- 2,925 miles away. The winner: Istvan Sipos, 
35, of Hungary, who made it in 68 days, beating the second-place finisher in 
handy fashion -- by 45 hours. . . . If you're thinking about entering next 
year's race, it's in June, and the starting point again is Huntington Beach. 
</P>
<P>
 TAKING STALK: When Julie Gianatassio, a senior at Western State University law 
school in Fullerton, worked with its domestic violence clinic this past year, 
she decided to put together a California stalking laws booklet. . . . The law 
school was so impressed it's now making it available to the public. It tells 
you whether you qualify as a stalking victim, and what legal remedies are 
available. "People think only of celebrities as stalking victims," says 
Gianatassio, who recently took the bar exam. "But many women out there face 
this threat." 
</P>
<P>
 CONCEPT SURFING: Maybe it helps to see what you're doing when you windsurf, 
but it's not really necessary to make it fun. . . . The Braille Institute in 
Anaheim has sent 30 teen-agers on a camping outing at Newport Dunes in Newport 
Beach for a three-day outing -- sailing, windsurfing, and setting up their own 
tents. "We call it conceptual development," says youth coordinator Peggy 
Comstock. "When you're blind, it's much easier to understand what you're 
reading if you've actually experienced it." 
</P>
</TEXT>
