<HEADLINE>
<P>
VAN IN BOSTON LINKED TO STUDENT'S SLAYING; CRIME: POLICE ARREST TWO YOUTHS IN 
VEHICLE BELIEVED THE ONE USED IN GARDEN GROVE KILLING. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARK I. PINSKY, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 An Orange County man and a juvenile were arrested in Boston Thursday in a van 
police say was involved in the shocking murder last week of a UCI engineering 
student gunned down in Garden Grove as he attempted to get the van's license 
number, police said. 
</P>
<P>
 Robert Sapinoso, 19, of Westminster was shot Aug. 17 as he and a friend 
followed a van he believed had been involved in neighborhood vandalism. He was 
hit several time in the upper body, then driven to a local hospital that did 
not have emergency facilities. He died before paramedics arrived. 
</P>
<P>
 "The van has been located in Boston," said Garden Grove police Capt. Dave 
Abrecht. "We're sending four investigators back there tonight to pick up the 
trail." 
</P>
<P>
 Garden Grove police Lt. John Woods said police stopped the van about 6 p.m. 
after a 10-minute chase. About four people were in the van, he said, but only 
two were held. They were a 17-year-old from Orange, who was arrested on a 
probation violation, and Vinh Quoc Ta, 18, of Santa Ana, arrested on a burglary 
warrant. 
</P>
<P>
 Boston police, like those in several other locations, had been advised by 
Garden Grove police to be on the lookout for the van. 
</P>
<P>
 "That is one of the places where we thought they might turn up," Abrecht said. 
</P>
<P>
 Dan Sapinoso, Robert's father, said he was "overwhelmed, overjoyed" to learn 
of the arrests. 
</P>
<P>
 "I just want justice to be done because we believe in justice in this country. 
. . . We are just happy that justice is being done." 
</P>
<P>
 Sapinoso's friend who was with him when the attack occurred, said he was "glad 
for Robert's parents. We wanted justice to be done." 
</P>
<P>
 Since the slaying, the friend said, "we've been doing a lot of praying here. 
We're a very religious family. I had really good faith that they were going to 
catch them. I'm totally relieved. The police did their job. They don't want it 
to happen again, and I don't want it happen again, and no one wants it to 
happen again." 
</P>
<P>
 However, he said, he was convinced those involved in the killing were part of 
a gang, so he was still "scared of the (gang members) coming back. It is a 
gang, so . . . I'm always going to have in my mind a worst-case scenario. . . . 
I'm going to have to watch out. The police are coming by here a lot. That's 
made my family feel better." 
</P>
<P>
 Sapinoso, an engineering student, had been working at the friend's house on 
their cars about 6:45 p.m. that day when they saw a passing silver Toyota van 
that matched the description of one used by vandals there the previous weekend. 
They got into Sapinoso's Honda CRX to follow it. 
</P>
<P>
 They had written all but one digit of the license plate when the van pulled 
over at Newland Street and Trask Avenue, and a passenger walked toward them and 
opened fire, the friend said. 
</P>
<P>
 He rushed Sapinoso to nearby Vencor Hospital-Orange County, which has no 
emergency facilities. Sapinoso died as they waited for help to arrive. 
</P>
<P>
 The friend told police the shooter was Vietnamese, between the 17 to 21 years 
of age, with "thick, black, unruly" hair. 
</P>
<P>
 Police on Thursday released a composite sketch of the gunman. 
</P>
<P>
 Times staff writer David Reyes contributed to this report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
