<HEADLINE>
<P>
RAMS TO DISCUSS RELEASING HENLEY RATHER THAN FACE CONDITIONS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By T.J. SIMERS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Rams are seriously considering the possibility of releasing cornerback 
Darryl Henley instead of committing to a $1-million bond that would free Henley 
to travel with the team this season. 
</P>
<P>
 Henley's bail restrictions on an indictment of cocaine possession and 
distribution prevented him from joining the team in San Diego's Jack Murphy 
Stadium Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
 A judge's ruling last week granted Henley permission to travel with the Rams 
with an increase in bail from $200,000 to $1 million, and with the proviso that 
a probation officer be with him at all times. 
</P>
<P>
 The Rams are concerned that the presence of a probation officer -- on the team 
plane, in team meetings and along the sideline -- might represent a 
considerable distraction. 
</P>
<P>
 A team official, who expressed serious concern about the $1-million bond, said 
the matter would be discussed Saturday in order to reach a determination before 
Sunday's required cut from 60 to 53 players. T.J. SIMERS 
</P>
</TEXT>
