<HEADLINE>
<P>
POLICE ARREST 2 ON DRUG CHARGES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE RYFLE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A doctor and his roommate were arrested Tuesday night for allegedly conducting 
an elaborate marijuana-growing operation inside their Glendale home. 
</P>
<P>
 Police found over an ounce of the drug, an array of sophisticated equipment 
used to grow marijuana plants indoors, plus pipes and smoking paraphernalia 
when they served a search warrant at the home of Dr. Eugene L. Herzog in the 
3400 block of Angeles Road. 
</P>
<P>
 Herzog, 49, is a physician with a practice in Los Angeles. He was booked for 
felony cultivation of marijuana and released later on $10,000 bail. Michael 
David Green, 31, who lived at the same address, faces identical charges, police 
said.  
</P>
<P>
 Police also found 12 marijuana plants at a North Hollywood address, where they 
believe Herzog and Green stashed them in anticipation of a possible police 
raid, said Detective Scott Bickle of the vice and narcotics bureau. 
</P>
<P>
 "It was very obvious as we walked into the house that there was a marijuana 
growing operation in the bedroom," Bickle wrote in a police report. He said 
there was evidence of marijuana throughout the house, even in the kitchen: 
"There was no room on the counter to prepare food without getting marijuana on 
your food." 
</P>
<P>
 Bickle said police acted on a tip from an unidentified informant. STEVE RYFLE 
</P>
</TEXT>
